Hartford July 27, 1889
Dear Bro:
I presume you have heard about all the unclear through your numerous friends. I know, I ought to have written before, but have been hindered, in various ways. You have, doubtless heard of my visit at unclear. I called upon Mr. Sawyer, and cannot say that he impressed me favorably, think he needs thawing out. And probably, his impression of me, was as much unclear, as you can imagine.
It has occured to me, unclear

I have some doubts as to my ability to confine myself to study. But I must say that at the present writing my mind is very much unsettled by reason of the struggle. I am unclear in trying to bare off my Tobacco. It must go in the course of three weeks or I can not enter the school.
